post_text:
GMSD Families,

We need your help! If you have not yet registered for school (which would include ALL students new, returning, whether in-person or fully virtual) please complete the process as soon as possible. Our staff needs accurate numbers of students enrolled in all of our programs to plan individual student schedules and staffing. These numbers are crucial for planning and communicating our Road to Reopen Plans at the individual school levels.

https://www.gmsdk12.org/Registration.aspx

If you've already registered within our Skyward Family Portal, please share this message with your friends and neighbors--especially those who may have incoming Kindergarten students or those new to GMSD.

Thank you for your help and continued collaboration.

Houston High School
March 31 at 10:15 AM ·

Congratulations to Eagle Scout Dean Stutler! He is with Boy Scout Troop 25. Dean worked with Plough Towers, a retirement center in Germantown, to address an acoustical issue. The center’s large main gathering area suffered terrible noise and echo issues after they removed the carpet. Dean designed, built and managed the install of 20 acoustical panels on the walls that did an incredible job to absorb the sound, so all the elderly residents could use the multi purpose room.
Congratulations, Dean on this outstanding accomplishment! Houston High Honors Academy

City of Germantown, Tennessee Government
March 25 at 10:45 AM ·

Good morning, Germantown!

If you have been on a walk in your neighborhood this week, you may have encountered some bears. There is no need to fear! We can confirm that these bears are completely harmless.

All over the country, people are placing teddy bears in their windows as an activity for children (and the kids at heart) during the COVID-19 quarantine. If you are looking for a fun activity for the family, take advantage of the sunshine this afternoon and go on a “bear hunt” in your neighborhood. Just remember, if you run into neighbors during your walk, please keep the CDC’s recommended 6 ft social distancing measures in mind.

We’d love to see your bear hunt pictures! Share pictures in the comments below or tag us in them. Stay strong, Germantown!

post_text:
GoNoodle created a free online resource GoNoodle: Good Energy at Home. It includes premium content and learning materials including movement and mindfulness videos as well as downloadable learning resources and ideas for off-screen activities - and if you sign up for email updates, they plan to send new ideas, activities, and tools to you weekly. There’s also a Good Energy channel on all GoNoodle home apps (iOS, Android, AppleTV, Fire, Roku) where all the best GoNoodle videos can be used by kids directly. Whether it takes the form of a family dance party, a song, and activity that reinforces something kids are learning at school, or a mindfulness or yoga video to help us all relieve stress and get a break from the intensity of it all - let’s all work to create Good Energy with our kids during this stressful time.

On a computer: https://www.gonoodle.com/good-energy-at-home-kids-games-and-videos/

On a mobile device: https://apps.apple.com/us/app/gonoodle-kids-videos/id1050712293

March 16, 2020

TRANSFER APPROVALS AND DENIALS
While we are hard at work preparing for the COVID-19 pandemic and the changes that occur each day, we want to make sure that families are updated on the transfer process. The Office of Student Services will be issuing Approval Letters via email by March 20, 2020. Please check spam and junk folders in your email. Denial Letters will be sent via postal mail no later than March 27, 2020. Please reach out to Kathy.dudley@gmsdk12.org with any questions.

Stay up-to-date by checking our webpage: http://www.gmsdk12.org/protected/ArticleView.aspx?iid=6GA0PI0&dasi=3G0I

post_text:
March 12, 2020--The six municipal Shelby County superintendents in Arlington, Bartlett, Collierville, Germantown, Lakeland, and Millington are aware of the decision of Shelby County Schools to cancel classes starting Friday, March 13th through March 30th.

At this time, neither the Shelby County Health Department nor the Tennessee Department of Education have made recommendations to close schools to contain the spread of the coronavirus or COVID-19.

As such, there are no plans to close municipal schools at this time, though the situation is fluid and we will make decisions on school closures as new information emerges.

We will continue to consult with the Shelby County Health Department and the Tennessee Department of Education to make decisions that are in the best interest of our students and staff.
